{"title_page": "Robert Destro", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Robert A. Destro\n|image        = Robert A. Destro official photo.jpg\n|state        = \n|district     = \n|term_start   = \n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Tom Malinowski]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n|president1   = \n|deputy1      = \n|term_start1  = September 23, 2019\n|term_end1    = \n|office2      = [[United States Commission on Civil Rights]]\n|term_start2  = 1983\n|term_end2    = 1989\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = \n|education    = [[Miami University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Juris Doctor]])\n|website      = \n}}\n'''Robert A. Destro''' is the [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]. He previously served on the [[United States Commission on Civil Rights]] from 1983 to 1989 and as a professor of law at [[The Catholic University of America]].<Ref name=wh/><ref name=Rasmussen/>\n\n==Education==\n\nDestro earned a B.A. from [[Miami University]] in Ohio, and a J.D. from the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=wh/>\n\n==Career==\nDestro was a professor of law and director of the Institute for Policy Research and Catholic Studies at [[The Catholic University of America]]'s [[Columbus School of Law]].<ref name=wh/><ref name=Rasmussen/> He taught at Catholic University since 1982 and served as an Interim Dean from 1999 to 2001.<ref name=wh/> He also founded the Interdisciplinary Program in Law & Religion at Catholic University.<ref name=Rasmussen/> \n\nDestro is a human rights advocate and a civil rights attorney with expertise in elections and employment law.<ref name=wh/> His legal work includes collaboration with the [[Peace Research Institute Oslo]] in a fifteen-year dialogue among Muslim, Christian, and Jewish legal, business, and religious leaders in the United States and the Middle East and efforts promoting the release of political prisoners and prisoners of conscience in the Middle East.<ref name=wh/>\n\nAs a U.S. civil rights commissioner from 1983 to 1989, Destro focused on disability-, national origin-, and religious-based discrimination.<ref name=Rasmussen/> From 1977 to 1982, he also served as General Counsel to the [[Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights]].<ref name=Rasmussen/> He was also special counsel to the [[Ohio Attorney General]] and the [[Ohio Secretary of State]] on election law matters from 2004 to 2006.<ref name=Rasmussen/><ref name=wh/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Rasmussen>{{cite news | last = Rasmussen | first = Renee | title = Catholic Law Professor Confirmed as Assistant Secretary for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor | date = October 3, 2019 | accessdate = October 3, 2019 | newspaper = The Tower | url = http://cuatower.com/2019/10/catholic-law-professor-confirmed-as-assistant-secretary-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor/}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=wh>{{cite web | url = https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key-administration-posts-48/ | title = President Donald J. Trump Announces His Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Posts | date = June 20, 2018 | publisher = The White House | accessdate = October 17, 2019 }} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Destro, Robert}}\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State]]\n[[Category:United States Commission on Civil Rights members]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Human rights]]\n[[Category:Columbus School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Robert A. Destro\n|image        = Robert A. Destro official photo.jpg\n|state        = \n|district     = \n|term_start   = \n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Tom Malinowski]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]\n|president1   = \n|deputy1      = \n|term_start1  = September 23, 2019\n|term_end1    = \n|office2      = [[United States Commission on Civil Rights]]\n|term_start2  = 1983\n|term_end2    = 1989\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = \n|education    = [[Miami University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Juris Doctor]])\n|website      = \n}}\n'''Robert A. Destro''' is the [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]]. He previously served on the [[United States Commission on Civil Rights]] from 1983 to 1989 and as a professor of law at [[The Catholic University of America]].<Ref name=wh/><ref name=Rasmussen/>\n\n==Education==\n\nDestro earned a B.A. from [[Miami University]] in Ohio, and a J.D. from the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=wh/>\n\n==Career==\nDestro was a professor of law and director of the Institute for Policy Research and Catholic Studies at [[The Catholic University of America]]'s [[Columbus School of Law]].<ref name=wh/><ref name=Rasmussen/> He taught at Catholic University since 1982 and served as an Interim Dean from 1999 to 2001.<ref name=wh/> He also founded the Interdisciplinary Program in Law & Religion at Catholic University.<ref name=Rasmussen/> \n\nDestro is a human rights advocate and a civil rights attorney with expertise in elections and employment law.<ref name=wh/> His legal work includes collaboration with the [[Peace Research Institute Oslo]] in a fifteen-year dialogue among Muslim, Christian, and Jewish legal, business, and religious leaders in the United States and the Middle East and efforts promoting the release of political prisoners and prisoners of conscience in the Middle East.<ref name=wh/>\n\nAs a U.S. civil rights commissioner from 1983 to 1989, Destro focused on disability-, national origin-, and religious-based discrimination.<ref name=Rasmussen/> From 1977 to 1982, he also served as General Counsel to the [[Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights]].<ref name=Rasmussen/> He was also special counsel to the [[Ohio Attorney General]] and the [[Ohio Secretary of State]] on election law matters from 2004 to 2006.<ref name=Rasmussen/><ref name=wh/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Rasmussen>{{cite news | last = Rasmussen | first = Renee | title = Catholic Law Professor Confirmed as Assistant Secretary for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor | date = October 3, 2019 | accessdate = October 3, 2019 | newspaper = The Tower | url = http://cuatower.com/2019/10/catholic-law-professor-confirmed-as-assistant-secretary-for-democracy-human-rights-and-labor/}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=wh>{{cite web | url = https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key-administration-posts-48/ | title = President Donald J. Trump Announces His Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Posts | date = June 20, 2018 | publisher = The White House | accessdate = October 17, 2019 }} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State]]\n[[Category:United States Commission on Civil Rights members]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Human rights]]\n[[Category:Columbus School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Destro"}
{"title_page": "Here's a Quarter (Call Someone Who Cares)", "text_new": "{{short description|1991 single by Travis Tritt}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Here's a Quarter (Call Someone Who Cares)\n| cover      = Travis Tritt - Heres a quarter - disc.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Travis Tritt]]\n| album      = [[It's All About To Change]]\n| B-side     = If I Had a Jukebox\n| released   = May 7, 1991\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 2:32\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = Travis Tritt\n| producer   = Gregg Brown\n| prev_title = [[Drift Off to Dream]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Anymore (Travis Tritt song)|Anymore]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n}}\n\"'''Here's a Quarter (Call Someone Who Cares)'''\" is a song written and recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Travis Tritt|Travis Tritt.]] It was released in May 1991 as the lead-off single to his album ''[[It's All About to Change]]''. It peaked at number 2 in both the United States<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=353}}</ref> and Canada. This is one of his most popular songs. When Travis would play this song live, fans would often throw quarters on stage, many hitting him.\n\n==Content==\nThe narrator speaks of a former significant other who regrets leaving him, and now wants to include herself in his life once again. However, the narrator no longer trusts her because of her actions.\n\nIn response, he gives her a quarter (in 1991, the common price for a local [[pay telephone]] call) and tells her to phone someone else who cares to listen.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by Gerry Wenner. The woman playing the role of the woman wanting the narrator of the song back is Leighanne Wallace, the future wife of [[Backstreet Boys]] member [[Brian Littrell]].\n\n==Personnel==\nThe following musicians play on this track:<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=It's All About to Change |others=Travis Tritt |year=1991 |type=CD booklet |publisher=Warner Bros. Records |id=26589}}</ref>\n* Sam Bacco \u2014 percussion\n* [[Richard Bennett (guitarist)|Richard Bennett]] \u2014 electric guitar, second solo\n* Mike Brignardello \u2014 bass guitar\n* [[Larry Byrom]] \u2014 acoustic guitar\n* [[John Cowan]] \u2014 background vocals\n* Wendell Cox \u2014 electric guitar, first solo\n* Terry Crisp \u2014 [[steel guitar]]\n* [[Stuart Duncan]] \u2014 fiddle\n* [[Bernie Leadon]] \u2014 electric guitar\n* [[Phil Madeira]] \u2014 [[Hammond B-3 organ]]\n* Tim Passmore \u2014 background vocals\n* [[Matt Rollings]] \u2014 piano\n* Jimmy Joe Ruggiere \u2014 harmonica\n* [[Russell Smith (singer)|Russell Smith]] \u2014 background vocals\n* Steve Turner \u2014 drums\n* [[Billy Joe Walker Jr.]] \u2014 electric guitar\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1991)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadacountry|2|chartid=1598|publishdate=August 17, 1991|accessdate=August 16, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|2|artist=Travis Tritt}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1991)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| Canada Country Tracks (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.1700&type=1&interval=24|title=RPM Top 100 Country Tracks of 1991|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=December 21, 1991|accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 22\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs|Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/1991/hot-country-songs| title=Best of 1991: Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=1991| accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 23\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|travis-tritt|heres-a-quarter-call-someone-who-cares}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Travis Tritt singles}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Here's A Quarter (Call Someone Who Cares)}}\n[[Category:1991 singles]]\n[[Category:Travis Tritt songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Travis Tritt]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:1991 songs]]\n\n{{1990s-country-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1991 single by Travis Tritt}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Here's a Quarter (Call Someone Who Cares)\n| cover      = Travis Tritt - Heres a quarter - disc.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Travis Tritt]]\n| album      = [[It's All About To Change]]\n| B-side     = If I Had a Jukebox\n| released   = May 7, 1991\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 2:32\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = Travis Tritt\n| producer   = Gregg Brown\n| prev_title = [[Drift Off to Dream]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Anymore (Travis Tritt song)|Anymore]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n}}\n\"'''Here's a Quarter (Call Someone Who Cares)'''\" is a song written and recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Travis Tritt]].  It was released in May 1991 as the lead-off single to his album ''[[It's All About to Change]]''.  It peaked at number 2 in both the United States<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=353}}</ref> and Canada. This is one of his most popular songs. When Travis would play this song live, fans would often throw quarters on stage, many hitting him.\n\n==Content==\nThe narrator speaks of a former significant other who regrets leaving him, and now wants to include herself in his life once again. However, the narrator no longer trusts her because of her actions.\n\nIn response, he gives her a quarter (in 1991, the common price for a local [[pay telephone]] call) and tells her to phone someone else who cares to listen.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by Gerry Wenner. The woman playing the role of the woman wanting the narrator of the song back is Leighanne Wallace, the future wife of [[Backstreet Boys]] member [[Brian Littrell]].\n\n==Personnel==\nThe following musicians play on this track:<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=It's All About to Change |others=Travis Tritt |year=1991 |type=CD booklet |publisher=Warner Bros. Records |id=26589}}</ref>\n* Sam Bacco \u2014 percussion\n* [[Richard Bennett (guitarist)|Richard Bennett]] \u2014 electric guitar, second solo\n* Mike Brignardello \u2014 bass guitar\n* [[Larry Byrom]] \u2014 acoustic guitar\n* [[John Cowan]] \u2014 background vocals\n* Wendell Cox \u2014 electric guitar, first solo\n* Terry Crisp \u2014 [[steel guitar]]\n* [[Stuart Duncan]] \u2014 fiddle\n* [[Bernie Leadon]] \u2014 electric guitar\n* [[Phil Madeira]] \u2014 [[Hammond B-3 organ]]\n* Tim Passmore \u2014 background vocals\n* [[Matt Rollings]] \u2014 piano\n* Jimmy Joe Ruggiere \u2014 harmonica\n* [[Russell Smith (singer)|Russell Smith]] \u2014 background vocals\n* Steve Turner \u2014 drums\n* [[Billy Joe Walker Jr.]] \u2014 electric guitar\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1991)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadacountry|2|chartid=1598|publishdate=August 17, 1991|accessdate=August 16, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|2|artist=Travis Tritt}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1991)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| Canada Country Tracks (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.1700&type=1&interval=24|title=RPM Top 100 Country Tracks of 1991|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=December 21, 1991|accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 22\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs|Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/1991/hot-country-songs| title=Best of 1991: Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=1991| accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 23\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|travis-tritt|heres-a-quarter-call-someone-who-cares}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Travis Tritt singles}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Here's A Quarter (Call Someone Who Cares)}}\n[[Category:1991 singles]]\n[[Category:Travis Tritt songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Travis Tritt]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:1991 songs]]\n\n{{1990s-country-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Deeayomi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor edit with spacing.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Here%27s_a_Quarter_(Call_Someone_Who_Cares)"}
{"title_page": "Achanak (1998 film)", "text_new": "{{Media IMDb refimprove|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Achanak<br>\u0905\u091a\u093e\u0928\u0915<br>{{Nastaliq|\u0627\u0686\u0627\u0646\u06a9}}\n| image          = Achanak (1998 film).jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Naresh Malhotra]]\n| producer       = [[Vijay Galani]]\n| writer         = [[Sachin Bhowmick]] (story & screenplay),<br>Anwar Khan (dialogues)\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]<br />[[Manisha Koirala]]<br />[[Farha Naaz]]<br/>\n[[Rahul Roy]] \n| music          = [[Dilip Sen-Sameer Sen]]\n| cinematography = Raju Kaygee\n| editing        = Naresh Malhotra\n| studio         = Film Folks,<br>Venus \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{start date|1998|6|12|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 159 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| website        = \n}}\n'''''Achanak''''' ({{lang-en|Suddenly}}) is an Indian action thriller film directed by Naresh Malhotra in [[Bollywood films of 1998|1998]]. During a song in the climax, [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]'s getup resembles [[Jim Carrey]]'s in ''[[The Mask (1994 film)|The Mask]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nWealthy industrialist Yashpal Nanda ([[Saeed Jaffrey]]) is widowed and lives with his daughter, Nisha (Pinky Singh), and two sons, Vijay ([[Rahul Roy]]), and Arjun ([[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]). He gets Nisha married to Nilesh ([[Dalip Tahil]]), while Vijay marries Madhu ([[Farah Naaz]]), and Yashpal is on the look-out for a suitable bride for Arjun. Arjun lives a charmed life, surrounded by the family he loves and working at his family's thriving business. Then he meets Pooja ([[Manisha Koirala]]), and his life gets even better. The two quickly fall in love. Yashpal is overjoyed and happy with Arjun's choice and cannot wait for them to get married. The Nanda family's world gets turned upside down when Nisha and then Vijay pass away suddenly, leaving the family devastated. Pooja is mistakenly convicted of murder, and Arjun must save her while he keeps up his family responsibilities, but his father soon meets a cruel end as well. The police arrive on the scene to arrest Arjun for murder.  Now, on the run from both the police and the mysterious criminals, Arjun and Pooja work to expose the truth while evading a fate at the hands of either.\n\n== Characters ==\n* [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]... Arjun\n* [[Manisha Koirala]]... Pooja\n* [[Farha Naaz]]... Madhu\n* [[Rahul Roy]]... Vijay\n* [[Johnny Lever]]... Joni/Moni/Toni Kapoor\n* [[Paresh Rawal]]... Sagar\n* [[Dalip Tahil]]...Nilesh\n* [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]]... Himself\n* [[Sanjay Dutt]]... Himself\n* [[Navneet Nishan]]... Anjali\n* [[Dinesh Hingoo]]... P.K Sharma\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Songs !! Singers\n|-\n|1 || \"Dil Le Gaya Chor Pakdo\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Johny Lever]]\n|-\n|2 || \"Duniya Bhulake\" || [[Kumar Sanu]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|3 || \"Ek Soni Kudi Dila De\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|4 || \"Jaane Jaana\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|5 || \"Na Koi Awaaz De Humko\" || [[Alka Yagnik]] and [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]]\n|-\n|6 || \"Oonchi Oonchi Deewaron Mein\" || [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|7 || \"Jhoomle\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0286421|title=Achanak}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dilip Sen-Sameer Sen]]\n\n\n{{1990s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Media IMDb refimprove|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Achanak<br>\u0905\u091a\u093e\u0928\u0915<br>{{Nastaliq|\u0627\u0686\u0627\u0646\u06a9}}\n| image          = Achanak (1998 film).jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Naresh Malhotra]]\n| producer       = [[Vijay Galani]]\n| writer         = [[Sachin Bhowmick]] (story & screenplay),<br>Anwar Khan (dialogues)\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]<br />[[Manisha Koirala]]<br />[[Farha Naaz]]<br/>\n[[Rahul Roy]] \n| music          = [[Dilip Sen-Sameer Sen]]\n| cinematography = Raju Kaygee\n| editing        = Naresh Malhotra\n| studio         = Film Folks,<br>Venus \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{start date|1998|6|12|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 159 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| website        = \n}}\n'''''Achanak''''' ({{lang-en|Suddenly}}) is an Indian action thriller film directed by Naresh Malhotra in [[Bollywood films of 1998|1998]]. Huge speculations were made that movie is a remake of Hollywood movie ''[[The Mask (1994 film)|The Mask]]'' due to the fact that actor [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] had a similar getup like [[Jim Carrey]]. However, his getup was merely for a song in the climax.\n\n==Plot==\nWealthy industrialist Yashpal Nanda ([[Saeed Jaffrey]]) is widowed and lives with his daughter, Nisha (Pinky Singh), and two sons, Vijay ([[Rahul Roy]]), and Arjun ([[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]). He gets Nisha married to Nilesh ([[Dalip Tahil]]), while Vijay marries Madhu ([[Farah Naaz]]), and Yashpal is on the look-out for a suitable bride for Arjun. Arjun lives a charmed life, surrounded by the family he loves and working at his family's thriving business. Then he meets Pooja ([[Manisha Koirala]]), and his life gets even better. The two quickly fall in love. Yashpal is overjoyed and happy with Arjun's choice and cannot wait for them to get married. The Nanda family's world gets turned upside down when Nisha and then Vijay pass away suddenly, leaving the family devastated. Pooja is mistakenly convicted of murder, and Arjun must save her while he keeps up his family responsibilities, but his father soon meets a cruel end as well. The police arrive on the scene to arrest Arjun for murder.  Now, on the run from both the police and the mysterious criminals, Arjun and Pooja work to expose the truth while evading a fate at the hands of either.\n\n== Characters ==\n* [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]... Arjun\n* [[Manisha Koirala]]... Pooja\n* [[Farha Naaz]]... Madhu\n* [[Rahul Roy]]... Vijay\n* [[Johnny Lever]]... Joni/Moni/Toni Kapoor\n* [[Paresh Rawal]]... Sagar\n* [[Dalip Tahil]]...Nilesh\n* [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]]... Himself\n* [[Sanjay Dutt]]... Himself\n* [[Navneet Nishan]]... Anjali\n* [[Dinesh Hingoo]]... P.K Sharma\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Songs !! Singers\n|-\n|1 || \"Dil Le Gaya Chor Pakdo\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Johny Lever]]\n|-\n|2 || \"Duniya Bhulake\" || [[Kumar Sanu]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|3 || \"Ek Soni Kudi Dila De\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|4 || \"Jaane Jaana\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|5 || \"Na Koi Awaaz De Humko\" || [[Alka Yagnik]] and [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]]\n|-\n|6 || \"Oonchi Oonchi Deewaron Mein\" || [[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]] and [[Alka Yagnik]]\n|-\n|7 || \"Jhoomle\" || [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] and [[Kavita Krishnamurthy]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0286421|title=Achanak}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dilip Sen-Sameer Sen]]\n\n\n{{1990s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Achanak_(1998_film)"}
{"title_page": "Forever Sounds", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Forever Sounds\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Wussy]]\n| cover      = File:Forever Sounds album cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2016|03|04}}\n| recorded   = Ultrasuede Studios, [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Indie rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Damnably]], [[Shake It Records]]\n| producer   = Jerri Queen, John Hoffman\n| prev_title = [[Attica!]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[What Heaven Is Like]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n}}\n'''''Forever Sounds''''' is [[Wussy]]'s sixth studio album. It was released on March 4, 2016, on [[Shake It Records]] in the United States and Damnably in the UK and Europe.<ref name=wussy>[http://wussy.ella.net/droppinghousesjan29/ Wussy Announce Sixth Album \u2018Forever Sounds\u2019 and Share New Track, \u2018Dropping Houses\u2019], [[Wussy]]</ref> The album reached number 20 on the [[Top Heatseekers]] album chart.<ref>http://www.billboard.com/artist/7257015/wussy/chart</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC=79/100<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/forever-sounds/wussy |title=Forever Sounds |website=Metacritic}}</ref>\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score={{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/forever-sounds-mw0002918176 |title=Forever Sounds  |last=Deming |first=Mark |website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n|rev7=''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|rev7score=8/10<ref name=spinreview/>\n|rev2=[[Robert Christgau]]\n|rev2score=A\u2013<ref name=xgau/>\n|rev5=''[[Pitchfork Media]]''\n|rev5score=6.9/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21651-forever-sounds/ |title=Forever Sounds |last=Monroe |first=Jazz |website=Pitchfork Media |publication-date=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n|rev6=''[[PopMatters]]''\n|rev6score={{rating|8|10}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/wussy-forever-sounds/ |title=Forever Sounds Review |last=Cober-Lake |first=Justin |website=PopMatters |publication-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n|rev4=''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n|rev4score=8/10<ref>{{cite web | url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/19294/reviews/4149849 | title=Forever Sounds Review | work=Drowned in Sound | date=2 March 2016 | accessdate=24 May 2017 | author=Adcock, Lee}}</ref>\n|rev3=''[[Cincinnati CityBeat]]''\n|rev3score=(favorable)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.citybeat.com/music/music-feature/article/13000688/review-wussys-forever-sounds | title=Sounds and Furies, Signifying Everything | work=Cincinnati CityBeat | date=17 February 2016 | accessdate=24 May 2017 | author=Baker, Brian}}</ref>\n}}\nUpon the album's release, ''SPIN'' named ''Forever Sounds'' its Album of the Week, awarding it an 8 of 10 rating. Reviewer Jason Gubbels wrote, \"The distinct pleasures of ''Forever Sounds'' remain those of all five preceding Wussy albums \u2014 a crack songwriting duo detailing adult life\u2019s ambiguities with vivid language amid a terrific rhythm section\u2019s unapologetic alt-slop.\"<ref name=\"spinreview\">[http://www.spin.com/2016/02/review-wussy-forever-sounds/ Review: Wussy\u2019s Ragged Ohio Racket Hits Biblical Proportions on \u2018Forever Sounds\u2019.]</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album an A- and described it as \"the big-guitar record I've been expecting from my favorite band since [[Strawberry (album)|Strawberry]].\"<ref name=xgau>{{cite web | url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/expert-witness-with-robert-christgau-beauty-pill-wussy-animal-collective | title=Guitar Rock Grooves | work=Vice | date=11 March 2016 | accessdate=11 March 2016 | author=Christgau, Robert}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n# Dropping Houses (Words: Lisa Walker, Chuck Cleaver) \n# She\u2019s Killed Hundreds (Cleaver) \n# Donny\u2019s Death Scene (Walker) \n# Gone (Cleaver) \n# Hello, I\u2019m a Ghost (Cleaver) \n# Hand of God (Walker) \n# Sidewalk Sale (Cleaver) \n# Better Days (Cleaver, Walker) \n# Majestic-12 (Walker) \n# My Parade (Cleaver)\n\nMusic on all tracks credited to Wussy.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Wussy}}\n[[Category:Wussy albums]]\n[[Category:2016 albums]]\n\n\n{{2010s-rock-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Forever Sounds\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Wussy]]\n| cover      = File:Forever Sounds album cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2016|03|04}}\n| recorded   = Ultrasuede Studios, [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Indie rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Damnably]], [[Shake It Records]]\n| producer   = Jerri Queen, John Hoffman\n| prev_title = [[Attica!]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[What Heaven Is Like]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n}}\n'''''Forever Sounds''''' is [[Wussy]]'s sixth studio album. It was released on March 4, 2016, on [[Shake It Records]] in the United States and Damnably in the UK and Europe.<ref name=wussy>[http://wussy.ella.net/droppinghousesjan29/ Wussy Announce Sixth Album \u2018Forever Sounds\u2019 and Share New Track, \u2018Dropping Houses\u2019], [[Wussy]]</ref> The album reached number 20 on the [[Top Heatseekers]] album chart.<ref>http://www.billboard.com/artist/7257015/wussy/chart</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC=79/100<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/forever-sounds/wussy |title=Forever Sounds |website=Metacritic}}</ref>\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score={{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/forever-sounds-mw0002918176 |title=Forever Sounds  |last=Deming |first=Mark |website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n|rev7=''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|rev7score=8/10<ref name=spinreview/>\n|rev6=[[Robert Christgau]]\n|rev6score=A\u2013<ref name=xgau/>\n|rev4=''[[Pitchfork Media]]''\n|rev4score=6.9/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21651-forever-sounds/ |title=Forever Sounds |last=Monroe |first=Jazz |website=Pitchfork Media |publication-date=9 March 2016}}</re